The subject Patient-Centred Communication focuses on the further application of the knowledge and skills acquired in the subject of Principles of Communication and Health Behaviour in Medicine in advising the patient on health-related topics. The structure and techniques of counseling are studied, which includes the involvement of the patient in the treatment process, finding and maintaining the focus of counseling, developing the patient's resources and making a common treatment plan. Interactions with different groups of patients (children, adolescents, the elderly, patients from different cultural backgrounds and patients with severe illness) are discussed. The subject provides knowledge on how to help people formulate their behavior change, to overcome the hesitations associated with behavior change, using their own beliefs, knowledge, skills, energy and commitment.
The structure of the course is based on the inverted classroom method, which gives the learner more freedom and also responsibility in the learning process. The ongoing evaluation is used. Learning materials include interactive learning objects that include recorded video lectures, relevant scientific literature, such as articles and textbook chapters, and problem-solving exercises and self-tests. Contact learning takes place in the form of seminars, where students apply previously developed theoretical knowledge in solving, analyzing and giving feedback on specific situation tasks.Objectives/eesmärkid:  A student who passed the subject has acquired an evidence-based basic knowledge of patient-centered communication and counseling and applies them in typical situations and has an idea of how to further develop their communication skills.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After passing the subject, the student: - understands the physical, mental and social factors influencing the perception of health risks and health behavior; - recognizes situations where basic skills and techniques of patient-centered communication, including counseling, can be used; - knows the peculiarities of communication with different patient groups; - is able to use patient-centered communication and motivation skills in conducting basic counseling and advising patients.
